node.text:
It’s a true wine spectacle! The Wine Room at @brennansnola reflects the glory of 75 years, 15,000 bottles, and a 16' slab of cypress which is located in the original carriage house and stable of the property. The historic 1795 building, designed by Edgar Degas’ grandfather has housed Brennan's since 1956 boasts a series of glamorous dining rooms, each resplendent with distinctive character, opulence, and whimsy.  And in the “cool” cellar, The Wine Room is a destination all its own. I spend a lot of time here, and you can see why! 

Follow along as I share a never- before- seen glimpse of our secret stash of rare spirits and vintages!

The lightly aged Clase Azul Reposado Tequila, smells, looks and tastes older and more complex than it is—it’s slightly fruity and sweet but with a complex character that pays off. Read our full review through the bio link.

node.text:
Rosé wine is the unofficial drink of summertime, sipped at the pool or on patios or picnics. You don’t have to be limited to merely drinking it straight from the bottle, though: Its fruity flavors lend themselves well to mixing up in a batch of Sangria. Whether in the bold style of Bandol rosés or a more gently aromatic Provencal one, or somewhere in between, that pink bottle is perfect for summertime Sangria drinking. Recipe in bio link.
-
photographer: @shadesofbooze 
stylist: @bar.histoire

node.text:
Gardenia mix takes the stage in the Pearl Diver from Jeff “Beachbum” Berry, giving the drink a spiced sweetness thanks to its combination of honey, butter, vanilla and spices. Blend it together with two kinds of rum, lime and orange juices, and a dash of bitters, then garnish with an edible orchid and a pineapple leaf to be transported straight to Tiki heaven. Recipe in bio link.
-

stylist: @bar.histoire

node.text:
A glass of good Sangria is one of the joys of summertime. The question is: Should you go red, white or rosé? Classic red Sangria brings deep, lush notes. But White Sangria goes lighter and brighter, not just with the wine that forms its base but the fruit within as well. Think stone fruits and bright citrus. Read more and our recipe through the link in the bio.
-
photographer: @shadesofbooze 
stylist: @bar.histoire

node.text:
Black rum was touted after Prohibition as a great base for punch. It works especially well in the classic Hurricane, where its richness is offset by tangy lemon and passion fruit. This version is from famed San Francisco Tiki bar Smuggler’s Cove. Recipe through our profile link.
-

stylist: @bar.histoire

node.text:
Essentially a boozy Arnold Palmer (and if you know anything about golf icons, you'll understand the punny source of this drink's name), the refreshing John Daly involves vodka, lemonade and iced tea, simply poured into a tall glass over ice and stirred to combine before garnishing with a lemon wheel. Recipe in bio link.
-
photographer: @shadesofbooze 
stylist: @bar.histoire

node.text:
From bartender and brand ambassador H. Joseph Ehrmann, the coconutty Chi Chi Organico will take you straight to the tropics. A vodka-based take on the Piña Colada, it calls for pineapple-flavored vodka, cream of coconut, heavy cream, pineapple puree and bitters to make a twist on the summer favorite—hollowed-out pineapple optional. Recipe in bio link. 
-
photographer: @shadesofbooze 
stylist: @bar.histoire

node.text: Visual appeal is increasingly important in the spirits category. “Package design is often the only opportunity to quickly tell customers everything they need to know about the brand,” says Joanne Campo, the communications director of Prestige Beverage Group. Read our article on how label or bottle changes can spike spirits sales through the bio link.

node.text:
Sometimes you just need something simple and quaffable. That’s where the Lincoln Club Cooler comes in. Like a lighter and more refreshing version of a Dark ’n Stormy, this cocktail keeps it low-key with just two ingredients—St. Croix rum and ginger ale—for a sparkling summer refresher. Recipe in bio link.
-
photographer: @shadesofbooze 
stylist: @bar.histoire

node.text:
The El Macuá is a fruity, tropical drink that will have you dreaming of summertime. Its bright flavors mean it’s no surprise the cocktail was named the national drink of Nicaragua, but the recipe is accessible enough that you can find all the ingredients at any ordinary grocery store: Rum, simple syrup and guava, orange and lemon juices are all you need, plus an orange slice and a candied cherry for garnish. Recipe in bio link.
-
photographer: @shadesofbooze 
stylist: @bar.histoire

node.text:
When it comes to entertaining a group there are two major contenders for the easiest and most satisfying large-scale libations: boozy bowls of punch and sweet-tart pitchers of iced tea and lemonade. With the LiberTea—made with black tea, lemonade, basil, bourbon and honey liqueur— there’s no need to choose between the two. Recipe in bio link.

stylist: @bar.histoire
